      <framework>axum</framework>
      <framework>actix-web</framework>
    </frameworks>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Rust HTTP Handlers (Axum)</title>

    <summary>Handler pattern for Axum (and Actix-web): typed request/response DTOs with validator derives, shared AppState behind Arc, AppError enum implementing IntoResponse, and #[tracing::instrument] on every handler. Handlers return Result&lt;Json&lt;Resp&gt;, AppError&gt;; extractors are ordered body-last.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Axum's type system encodes the request contract at compile time, eliminating an entire class of runtime panics. Without the structured AppError + extractor-order discipline, agents routinely produce handlers that panic on parse failure, expose database errors to clients, and fight the borrow checker on &amp;str parameters. The pattern also enables one-shot Router::oneshot unit tests with no network.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Building JSON REST APIs with Axum or Actix-web.</item>
        <item>Refactoring loosely-typed handlers into the request-DTO / service-call / response-DTO layered pattern.</item>
        <item>Adding validator-based request validation and typed error responses.</item>
        <item>Implementing streaming responses (SSE, WebSocket) with Tokio.</item>
        <item>Wiring middleware: tracing, CORS, auth, rate limiting via tower-http.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>High-throughput RPC where Tonic (gRPC) is a better fit.</item>
        <item>Async-light scripts and CLIs — reqwest + tokio without a server framework.</item>
        <item>Teams with more comfort in Go/Python where perf gain doesn't justify Rust compile times.</item>
        <item>Frontends serving lots of HTML — consider leptos/dioxus ecosystems.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="handler-pattern-extractors-dtos-responses">
      <p>Defines the canonical Axum handler structure: extractor ordering (State first, body last), request DTOs with validator derives, response DTOs with From&lt;Model&gt; impls, and consistent return types.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Order Axum extractors: State first, path/query parameters next, body (Json&lt;T&gt;) last. Body extractors consume the request; placing them before path/query compiles but body extractors after another body extractor will not compile.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum processes extractors in declaration order. Json&lt;T&gt; consumes the request body; a second body extractor after it finds an empty stream and panics or returns an error.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Proper extractor ordering">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[
pub async fn create(
    State(state): State<AppState>,         // 1. state first
    Path(id): Path<i32>,                   // 2. path params
    Json(payload): Json<CreateUserRequest>, // 3. body last
) -> Result<(StatusCode, Json<UserResponse>), AppError> {
    payload.validate()?;
    // ...
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Placing Json&lt;T&gt; before State or Path parameters.</description>
        <reason>Does not fail at compile time (just extractor ordering) but produces confusing behavior when State is added later and causes trait bound errors.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule>
        <statement>Define separate request DTOs (with Deserialize + Validate derives) and response DTOs (with Serialize). Implement From&lt;Model&gt; for response DTOs. Never expose domain models directly in handlers.</statement>
        <rationale>Decoupling request shape from the domain model lets both evolve independently. From&lt;Model&gt; implementations are compile-checked and avoid ad-hoc field mapping in handlers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Request and response DTOs with separation">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[
#[derive(Debug, Deserialize, Validate)]
pub struct CreateUserRequest {
    #[validate(length(min = 2, max = 100))]
    name: String,
    #[validate(email)]
    email: String,
    #[validate(length(min = 8))]
    password: String,
}

#[derive(Debug, Serialize)]
pub struct UserResponse {
    id: i32,
    name: String,
    email: String,
    created_at: chrono::DateTime<chrono::Utc>,
}

impl From<User> for UserResponse {
    fn from(user: User) -> Self {
        Self { id: user.id, name: user.name,
               email: user.email, created_at: user.created_at }
    }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>AppState must implement Clone. Wrap all non-Clone resources in Arc. Never put &amp;str, non-Send types, or borrowed data in AppState.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum clones AppState for each request. Non-Clone types cause compile errors; non-Send types violate the async executor's thread-safety requirement.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Putting a raw DbPool or Config struct directly in AppState without Arc.</description>
        <reason>Forces a full clone of potentially large structs per request. Use Arc&lt;DbPool&gt; and Arc&lt;Config&gt; instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="app-error-enum-thiserror-intoresponse-scrubbing">
      <p>AppError enum using thiserror for display, implementing IntoResponse to map variants to HTTP status codes and safe JSON bodies, with internal errors scrubbed before reaching the client.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Define AppError as a thiserror enum with one variant per error class. Use #[from] derives for sqlx::Error, validator::ValidationErrors, reqwest::Error, and anyhow::Error so ? works everywhere. Implement IntoResponse to map variants to (StatusCode, Json) tuples.</statement>
        <rationale>thiserror generates Display automatically from the #[error("...")] attribute, eliminating manual fmt::Display implementations. #[from] derives let ? propagate library errors into AppError without explicit map_err calls.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <reference path="templates/app_error.rs">Full AppError enum with IntoResponse implementation.</reference>

      <example type="good" title="thiserror AppError with From derives">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[
#[derive(Debug, Error)]
pub enum AppError {
    #[error("not found")]
    NotFound,
    #[error("unauthorized")]
    Unauthorized,
    #[error("validation: {0}")]
    Validation(#[from] validator::ValidationErrors),
    #[error("conflict: {0}")]
    Conflict(String),
    #[error("database: {0}")]
    Database(#[from] sqlx::Error),
    #[error("internal: {0}")]
    Internal(#[from] anyhow::Error),
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>In IntoResponse, map Database, Upstream, and Internal variants to "internal error" in the public message, regardless of the internal error text. Only NotFound, Unauthorized, Conflict, and Validation messages are client-safe.</statement>
        <rationale>Database error text contains table names, column names, constraint names, and sometimes query fragments — all sensitive. The internal error is already captured by tracing::error! for server-side correlation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="IntoResponse with message scrubbing">
        <code lang="rust"><![CDATA[
impl IntoResponse for AppError {
    fn into_response(self) -> Response {
        let (status, code) = match &self {
            AppError::NotFound       => (StatusCode::NOT_FOUND, "NOT_FOUND"),
            AppError::Unauthorized   => (StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED, "UNAUTHORIZED"),
            AppError::Validation(_)  => (StatusCode::UNPROCESSABLE_ENTITY, "VALIDATION_ERROR"),
            AppError::Conflict(_)    => (StatusCode::CONFLICT, "CONFLICT"),
            AppError::Database(_)
            | AppError::Internal(_)  => (StatusCode::INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR, "INTERNAL_ERROR"),
        };
        let msg = match &self {
            AppError::Database(_) | AppError::Internal(_) => "internal error".to_string(),
            other => other.to_string(),
        };
        tracing::error!(error = %self, "request failed");
        (status, Json(json!({ "error": { "code": code, "message": msg } }))).into_response()
    }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="rules-no-str-no-unwrap-cargo-check-loop">
      <p>Concrete rules for Axum handler authoring that prevent the most common compiler errors and runtime panics produced by LLM-generated code.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>All handler function parameters must be owned types (String, not &amp;str). Lifetime parameters do not satisfy Axum's Handler trait bound.</statement>
        <rationale>Axum handlers must be Send + 'static. References with non-static lifetimes break this invariant. Agents trained on sync examples emit &amp;str; always replace with String.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Never use .unwrap() or .expect() in handler code paths. Use ? to propagate into AppError. Block unwrap_used via clippy: -D clippy::unwrap_used.</statement>
        <rationale>unwrap() panics on None/Err, which terminates the current task and may leak resources. Axum catches panics but the response is a 500 with no body context.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use cargo check as the primary feedback loop during handler development (10x faster than cargo build). Run cargo build + cargo test only before commit.</statement>
        <rationale>cargo check type-checks without linking. For Axum with its generic extractor machinery, full builds are expensive. cargo check catches 95% of errors in &lt;5s.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test handlers with Router::oneshot(Request::builder()...) — no real server needed. This approach is fast, parallel-safe, and tests the full extractor + middleware chain.</statement>
        <rationale>Spinning a real server for tests adds port-conflict flakiness and startup overhead. oneshot runs the full handler pipeline in-process.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding 'a lifetime parameters to handler signatures to "fix" &amp;str params.</description>
        <reason>Lifetime params do not satisfy Axum's Into&lt;Router&gt; bound. The correct fix is to use String (owned) or 'static &amp;str constants.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Placing sqlx::query! without DATABASE_URL or .sqlx/ offline files in CI.</description>
        <reason>sqlx queries are verified at compile time; CI builds without DATABASE_URL set will fail. Use SQLX_OFFLINE=true and check in .sqlx/.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Using std::sync::Mutex inside async handlers.</description>
        <reason>Holding a std::sync::MutexGuard across .await deadlocks the Tokio runtime. Use tokio::sync::Mutex or prefer message-passing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-and-ai-agent-gotchas">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use thiserror for the error enum, anyhow::Error only for the catch-all variant; convert via From impls so ? works everywhere.</statement>
        <rationale>Provides typed error handling with minimal boilerplate.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Wrap every handler in #[tracing::instrument(skip(state), fields(user_id))]; structured logs become free.</statement>
        <rationale>Enables automatic request tracing and observation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep AppState cheaply cloneable: Arc&lt;DbPool&gt;, Arc&lt;HttpClient&gt;, Arc&lt;Config&gt;. Never put &amp;str or non-Send types.</statement>
        <rationale>AppState is cloned per-request; non-Send types violate async safety.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use axum-extra::TypedHeader for typed headers (Authorization, Content-Type) instead of parsing strings.</statement>
        <rationale>Compile-time safety for HTTP headers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Pin tokio + tower + axum in Cargo.toml; ecosystem is fast-moving and minor bumps break agent-generated code.</statement>
        <rationale>Ensures reproducible builds and prevents breakage from dependency updates.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Test handlers with Router::oneshot(Request::builder()...) — fast and hermetic, no network needed.</statement>
        <rationale>Enables fast, unit-test-style handler testing without spinning up servers.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Generate OpenAPI from types (utoipa / aide); ship openapi.json in CI to detect contract drift.</statement>
        <rationale>Automatically generated documentation catches API contract changes.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>unwrap() and expect() in prod paths because they look harmless to LLMs.</description>
        <reason>Block via clippy -D unwrap_used; panics crash the Tokio task.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>&amp;str as a handler param doesn't compile (no 'static lifetime); agent's first fix is often wrong ('a lifetime).</description>
        <reason>Force String; the agent's lifetime fix won't satisfy Axum's Handler trait.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Extractor order errors produce confusing trait-bound messages; agent loops on compile errors.</description>
        <reason>Hint that body extractors must come last.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>sqlx::query! requires DATABASE_URL at compile time or .sqlx/ offline files. Agents miss the offline step in CI.</description>
        <reason>Use SQLX_OFFLINE=true and check in .sqlx/.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>tracing::info! without target = overflows logs in hot paths.</description>
        <reason>Require sampling for high-QPS endpoints.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Async + std::sync::Mutex creates deadlocks. Agents reach for sync::Mutex in async code.</description>
        <reason>Use tokio::sync::Mutex (or RwLock) only when needed; prefer message-passing.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Any new dep in Cargo.toml, unsafe block, or tokio::spawn with unbounded lifetime needs approval.</description>
        <reason>Compile times and runtime correctness regress quickly; human-in-loop checkpoint required.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/app_error.rs" purpose="Full AppError enum with IntoResponse (thiserror + axum)."/>
      <template path="templates/handler_example.rs" purpose="CRUD handler set: list, get, create, update, delete."/>
    </templates>

